1. Gender Labor Participation Gaps and Public Sector size

In the first geovisualiztion we follow-up on the previous Female Labor Participation Trends analysis for OECD countries, merging our previous LFP and public spending dataset with a world map shapefile.

Essentially, the plot below shows the same correlations we saw in the past write-up regarding participation gaps, public sector size, and regional clustering, but more succintly summarized in a world map with an embedded bar chart displaying the labor participation gap alligned with each countrys latitude.

theme_ebg <- theme(line=element_line(size=0.5, lineend = 'round' ),

####### I. Data Loading and Pre-processing 

### I.1 Hours Worked and Skill Mismatch

# Hours worked dataset:
hoursw <- read.csv("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/flp/data/oecd_hoursw.csv")

#  Function to create 'region' column:

add_region <- function(df) {
  df <- mutate(df, Region = ifelse(Country %in% c('Sweden', 'Norway','Denmark','Finland'), "Nordic",
                                   ifelse(Country %in% c('Spain', 'Italy', 'Portugal', 'Greece'), "Mediterranean",
                                          ifelse(Country %in% c('Russian Federation', 'Lithuania','Latvia',
                                                                'Estonia',  'Slovenia', 'Slovak Republic'), 'Eastern Europe',
                                                 ifelse(Country %in% c('Japan', 'Korea'), 'Asia',
                                                        ifelse(Country %in% c('Germany', 'Netherlands','Luxembourg', 'France',
                                                                              'Hungary', 'Poland', 'Austria', 'Belgium', 'Czech Republic',
                                                                              'Switzerland'), 'Western Europe', 
                                                               ifelse(Country %in% c('Australia', 'Canada', 'United States',
                                                                                     'United Kingdom','Ireland', 'New Zealand' ),'Anglo-Saxon',
                                                                      'Rest')))))))
  return(df)
}

hoursw <- add_region(hoursw) 

# Obtain mean weekly hours worked on average over 1980-2017 for each country:
means <- hoursw %>% 
  group_by(Country, Region) %>% 
  summarise(av_hours = mean(Value, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(av_hours)

# Add job mismatch data to the small summary dataset:
mism <- read.csv("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/flp/data/mism.csv")
mism_oq <- filter(mism, Indicator %in% c('Overqualification'))
#means <- merge(means, mism_oq, by = c("Country"), all.x = TRUE) # not helpful, too broad

hw_mm <- merge(hoursw, mism_oq, by = c("Country"), all.x = TRUE)
hw_mm_16 <- filter(hw_mm, Time.x == 2016)

## I. 2 Public Sector Size, Population, and LFP

# Load and process employment participation rate data:
epr <- read.csv("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/flp/data/lfs.csv")
epr <-  add_region(epr) 
epr_allage <- filter(epr, AGE %in% c('1564'))

# Labour force participation rate:
lfp <- filter(epr_allage, Series %in% c('Labour force participation rate'))

lfpw <- filter(lfp, SEX %in% c('WOMEN')) # fem lfs
lfpmw <- filter(lfp, SEX %in% c('MEN'))
lfpmw$LFP_W <- lfpw$LFP

##########  IV. Public Expenditures by Type and Women LFP

# Government Size: measured as the ratio of total taxation to GDP
tax <- read.csv("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/flp/data/tax.csv")
total_tax <- filter(tax, TAX %in% c('TOTALTAX'))
names(total_tax)[names(total_tax) == 'Year'] <- 'Time'
df <- merge(lfpmw, total_tax, by = c("Country", "Time")) 
names(df)[names(df) == 'Value'] <- 'Tax'

# Load and process job strain data:
jobq <- read.csv("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/flp/data/jobq.csv")
jobq <- filter(jobq, Age== 'Total')
jobq <- filter(jobq, Components == 'Job Strain')
jobq <- filter(jobq, Education == 'Total')
jobq <- filter(jobq, Sex == 'Total')

JSindex<- jobq %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% 
  summarise(JobStrain = mean(Value))

# Add job strain index to the dataset:
df_LGQ <- merge(df, JSindex, by = c("Country"), all.x = TRUE) # lfp, tax, jobstr
gov_exp <- read.csv("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/flp/data/gov_exp.csv")

gov_exp$Indicator <- sub(", percentage of GDP.*", "", gov_exp$Indicator)
gov_exp$Indicator <- sub("General government expenditure by function,*", "", gov_exp$Indicator)
gov_exp$Indicator <- sub(", percentage of total expenditure of general government (GG)*", "", gov_exp$Indicator)
gov_exp$Indicator <- sub(", percentage of total expenditure of GG*", "", gov_exp$Indicator)

gov_exp <- filter(gov_exp, !Indicator %in% c('Net lending/net borrowing, General government',
                                             'Total general government (GG) revenue', 'Net saving of General Government',
                                             'Adjusted debt of general government', 'Gross debt of general government',
                                             ' total expenditure', 'Social benefits other than social transfers in kind',
                                             'Social transfers in kind'))
gov_exp$Indicator <- sub("(GG).*", "", gov_exp$Indicator)
gov_exp <- gov_exp %>% drop_na(Indicator)
df2 <- merge(df_LGQ, gov_exp, by = c("Country", "Time"), all.x = TRUE)
df2_2015 <- filter(df2, Time %in% c(2015))
tot_sp <- filter(gov_exp, Indicator %in% c('Social benefits and social transfers in kind')) 

df3 <- merge(df2, tot_sp, by = c("Country", "Time"), all.x = TRUE)
av_mw_dif <- df3 %>% 
  summarise(global_mw_dif  = mean(mw_dif))

WLFP_dev <- df3 %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% 
  summarise(av_mwdif = (mean(mw_dif) - av_mw_dif$global_mw_dif) / av_mw_dif$global_mw_dif)

df3 <- merge(df3, WLFP_dev, by = c("Country"), all.x = TRUE)
df3 <- mutate(df3, SignWLFP = ifelse(av_mwdif > 0, "Above Average Male-Female LFP",
                                     "Below Average Male-Female LFP"))
soc_exp <- read.csv("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/flp/data/social_exp.csv")
soc_exp <- filter(soc_exp, !Branch %in% c('Health', 'Old age', 'Total')) 
soc_exp_str <- soc_exp %>% 
  na.omit() %>%
  group_by(Country, Branch) %>% 
  summarise(av_spend = mean(Value))
soc_exp_str <- mutate(soc_exp_str, ratio_spend = av_spend/sum(av_spend))
soc_exp_str <- filter(soc_exp_str, Branch =='Family')
df5 <- merge(df3, soc_exp_str, by = c("Country"))
df5 <-rename(df5, Public.Spending.Branch = Branch)
df5 <- filter(df5, Time==2015)
df5 <- filter(df5, Public.Spending.Branch=='Family')
df5 <- df5 %>% distinct(av_mwdif, .keep_all = TRUE)

### World Shapefile
world <- ne_countries(scale = "medium", returnclass = "sf")
world <-rename(world,  Country=sovereignt)
world$Country[world$Country %in% "United States of America"] <- "United States"
dfw <- left_join(df5, world, by='Country')
dfw$mw<-cut(dfw$mw_dif, seq(0, 50, 5), right=FALSE, labels=c(1:10))

dfw <- dfw %>%
  st_as_sf(na.fail = FALSE, crs = 4326) 

world_points<- st_centroid(dfw)
world_points <- cbind(dfw, st_coordinates(st_centroid(dfw$geometry)))

ggplot(data = dfw) +
  theme_ebg +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(size=0.5, colour = "grey90", fill = 'midnightblue')) +
  ggtitle("Lower Gender Labor Participation Gaps: Larger Public Sectors") +
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title='Public Sector Size')) +
  labs(subtitle = "Labor participation gap between men and women tends to be lower in countries\n with higher public sector size",
       caption = "Source: OECD Statistics, 2016 \n Note: Gender LFP gap is measured as the absolute difference between male and female labor force participation ratios. \n
       Public Sector size is measured as the ratio of total tax revenue over GDP") +
  xlab("") + ylab("") +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Tax), size=0.25, alpha=0.75, color = 'black') +
  geom_col(data= world_points, aes(x=X, y=mw_dif, width=2, fill=Tax), 
            alpha=0.8) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "ivory", high = "red2") +
  annotate("text", x=-160, y=38, label="Gender LFP Gap\n (percentage points (min=0, max=50))", 
           size =1.5, color='white', family = "Trebuchet MS")

2. City of Austin: 311 Requests Resolution and OIS Cases

In this visualization we merge two datasets with a shapefile in order to explore some geospatial trends in the city of Austin, Texas. The first dataset contains all 311 requests made in 2015. The second dataset contains all occurrences of fatal Officer-Involved Fatal Shootings (OIS) for the City of Austin.

Though its not something strikingly clear in the data, several other variables and , fatal OIS cases tend to occur in areas away from the center, which has the highest concentration of resolved (versus open) 311 requests. Of course, its important to keep in mind that there could be several confounding variables driving this trend.

####### LOAD DATASETS: SHP, 311, and OIS

dftx_shp <- read_sf(dsn = "/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/GeoViz/data/TX_tract/tl_2017_48_tract.shp")
df311<- read_sf("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/GeoViz/data/311_data.csv")
df3ois<- read_sf("/Users/elenabg/exploratory_LFP/GeoViz/data/OIS_08_17.csv")

# Extract coordinates form Location column:
n = 0
df3ois$Loc <- sub(paste('.+(?=.{', n, '})', sep=''), '',df3ois$`Location 1`, perl=T)
df3ois$Y <- sub(paste('.+(?=.{', 10, '})', sep=''), '',df3ois$Loc, perl=T)
df3ois$X <- substr(df3ois$Loc, start=2, stop=11)
df3ois$X <- substr(df3ois$Loc, start=3, stop=10)
df3ois$Y <- substr(df3ois$Loc, start=12, stop=22)
df3ois$X <- str_replace(df3ois$X, ",", "")
df3ois$Y <- str_replace(df3ois$Y, ",", "")

df3ois$year <- format(as.Date(df3ois$Date, format = '%m/%d/%Y'), '%Y')
df3ois <- tail(df3ois, -2)
df3ois <-rename(df3ois, Injury = 'Subject Injuries')
df3ois <-rename(df3ois, Case = 'Case #')

df3ois <- filter(df3ois, X < 31)
df3ois <- filter(df3ois, X > 29)
df3ois <- filter(df3ois, !Case == "10-5068185\n10-3572205")

df3oisK <- filter(df3ois, Injury== "killed")

dfoisgeo <- df3ois %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("Y", "X"), na.fail = FALSE, crs = 4326) 

dfoisgeok <- df3oisK %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("Y", "X"), na.fail = FALSE, crs = 4326) 

df311 <-rename(df311, Y = 'Longitude Coordinate')
df311 <-rename(df311, X = 'Latitude Coordinate')
df311<-rename(df311, Type = 'SR Description')
df311<-rename(df311, Status = 'SR Status')
df311<-rename(df311, Date = 'Created Date')
df311$year <- format(as.Date(df311$Date, format = '%m/%d/%Y'), '%Y')

# Only cols of interest
df311_red <- subset(df311, select = c(Type, X, Y, Status, Date, County, year))

# Convert to sf
df311geo <- df311_red %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("Y", "X"), na.fail = FALSE, crs = 4326) 

#Set congruent crs for shpfile
dftx_shp <- st_set_crs(dftx_shp, 4326)


#df311geo_type <- filter(df311geo, Type %in% c('Loud Music', 'Pothole Repair'))
df311geo_resolv <- filter(df311geo, Status %in% c('Resolved', 'Open'))
df311geo15 <- filter(df311geo_resolv, year==2015)

dfsp_aus <- st_join(dftx_shp, df311geo15, join = st_intersects, left = FALSE) %>%
  st_as_sf(crs = 4326, na.fail = FALSE)

####### PLOTTING

# Build arbitrary color palettes for regions:
gg_color_hue <- function(n) {
  hues = seq(15, 375, length=n+1)
  hcl(h=hues, l=65, c=100)[1:n]
}
statuscols <- gg_color_hue(length(unique(df311geo15$Status)))
names(statuscols) <- unique(df311geo15$Status)

statuscols["Open"] <- "red3"
statuscols["Resolved"] <- "cyan3"

ggplot() + 
  theme_ebg +
  geom_sf(data=dfsp_aus, size = 0.25, fill="ivory", colour="wheat3") +
  geom_sf(data=df311geo15, mapping=aes(color=Status, fill=Status), size=2, pch=21) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=statuscols) +
  scale_colour_manual(values=statuscols) +
  geom_sf(data=dfoisgeok, pch=24, size=4, fill="gold", color="orange") +
  ggtitle("Fatal OIS and 311 Request Resolution Status: Austin, TX\n ") +
  labs(subtitle = "Geographic distribution for the occurrence of fatal OIS cases seems slightly more concentrated away \n from areas with highest number of Resolved 311 Requests",
       caption = "Source: City of Austin Open Data Portal and U.S. Census Bureau.\n Note: Each point represents an occurrence.\n Data for 311 Requests corresponds to 2015. Data for OIS Cases corresponds to from 2010-2016, including all publicly available data.") +
annotate("label", label = 'Fatal OIS', alpha=0.85, x = -97.5, y = 30.1,
           size= 8, family = "Trebuchet MS", color='gold', font='bold')
